<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Opinions on automatic code doccumentation tools ?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=10420&amp;p=117136#p117136"><![CDATA[
I've used Doxygen for professional work. I think it works okay. Also, you can make one line Doxygen comments if you want, and it's generally just one extra character to identify the comment as documentation, so I don't think the complaint about verbosity is valid.<br /><br />In addition to the documentation attached to discrete elements of code, it's important to make high level overviews as well, but because it isn't as convenient as inline notation, this part often gets overlooked. Automated documentation system generally do have ways to include stuff like this with the generated HTML, though. It's also important that the documentation system have ways to decorate related classes/terms with a hyperlink.<br /><br />The other side of it is that programmers who dislike writing documentation (which I think is at least half of programmers) who are told to document everything will do a crummy job of it regardless of the tools available. Sometimes a bunch of badly written Doxygen comments are worse than no comments at all, since they're just adding noise and filler that takes away from the useful documentation in the system.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=5165">rainwarrior</a> — Tue Aug 27, 2013 8:11 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
