<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Opinions on automatic code doccumentation tools ?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=10420&amp;p=117119#p117119"><![CDATA[
I myself don't use those &quot;extra gibberish things around [my] comments&quot;. Writing a proper document with everything by sections usually work better. However, in Haskell uses a similar thing but Haskell does use sections and extra text, the syntax for the description isn't as long as these, and it does automatically create a documentation HTML with cross-references of all the types and everything used; the type of each thing is automatically documented and you can optionally add a description and/or sections too. However, in the (old) version I used, the documentation comments have to be a statement by themself in order to work, so you need a semicolon afterward (and in a single-line comment, you cannot put them on the same line as the comment, so you have to put them on the next line). I don't know if this problem has been corrected yet.<br /><br />There is also WEB, which does a different kind of code documentation. In a WEB program, basically it is a document which contains pieces of Pascal code (an extended variant of Pascal, with features such as macros, octal and hexadecimal literals, and pool strings), which can also contain references to other pieces of codes, and the compiler puts them all together in the right order and generates an index and so on. TeX is written in WEB, and TeX is also used to print out TeX the program itself, in a book which I have. However, it is meant for whole programs rather than program libraries, and seems to be very good for writing a paper about the algorithms used, would be one use of it.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4734">zzo38</a> — Mon Aug 26, 2013 8:16 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
